        <h3><%= t(".laptop-setup", :default => "Laptop Setup") %></h3>
        <p>If you're looking to get a good Ruby on Rails development environment installed on Mac OS X, install XCode (from a CD if you have it, otherwise <a href="http://developer.apple.com/technologies/tools/xcode.html">download it</a>), then:</p>
<pre><code>ruby -e "$(curl -fsSL https://gist.github.com/raw/323731/install_homebrew.rb)"
brew install postgres imagemagick redis git
bash < <( curl http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/releases/rvm-install-head )
rvm install 1.9.2-p136
rvm --default use 1.9.2
gem install bundler suspenders heroku
ssh-keygen
git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "your_email@whatever.com"</code></pre>
        <p>Here's how to create a Rails app with thoughtbot's standards included, then deploy it to Heroku:</p>
<pre><code>suspenders create my-app
cd my-app
heroku create
git push heroku master
</code></pre>
        <h3><%= t(".brushing-up", :default => "Brushing Up") %></h3>
        <p>The more the class is familiar with the enabling technologies of Ruby on Rails development and deployment, the more we can cover in the class. We'll be using git, HTML, and SQL at times during the class, so we would appreciate if you brush up on some of these skills if they are new to you or you don't use them that often.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Sharpen your version control skills with <a href="http://gitimmersion.com/lab_03.html">Git Immersion</a>. It's a quick interactive tutorial.</li>
          <li>Brush up on the latest in web standards with <a href="http://diveintohtml5.org/">Dive Into HTML5</a>. It's a free, very detailed overview of HTML5.</li>
          <li>If you're new to SQL or just haven't memorized some things, use this <a href="http://www.cryer.co.uk/brian/sql/sql_crib_sheet.htm">SQL crib sheet</a>. It's only what you need. No more, no less.</li>
        </ul>
        <h3><%= t(".reference-rails", :default => "Reference: Ruby on Rails") %></h3>
        <p>These two free resources are excellent to have by your side day-to-day, after the class, when you're developing and need to look something up.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><a href="http://railsapi.com/doc/rails-v3.0.3/">Ruby on Rails API</a>: This version of the docs has a killer "fast search" feature.</li>
          <li><a href="http://guides.rubyonrails.org/">Ruby on Rails Guides</a>: When you need a quick refresher on routing, or what ActiveRecord's new syntax is, or how to send e-mail, go here.</li>
        </ul>
